version, and the construction of gender. Drawing on research in a series of previously unedited charters and the earliest glossa manuscripts, she demonstrates that this method of constructing reality was a constitutive element of the thought of the period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aOpposition, Theory ofxHistoryyTo 1500. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aReligious Studies.  amedieval thinkers, France, dialectical reasoning, medieval studies, interaction of religious thinkers, culture of the Middle Ages, high medieval thought.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150171665240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501716652423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501716652/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles